Introduction¶

The great state of North Carolina and its 100 counties make for a diverse place, with both urban and rural, richer and poorer areas. Today, the state capital of Raleigh is a thriving research-based region, while the city of Charlotte is the 2nd largest Banking center in the US after New York. However, there are obvious concerns related to violence and crime statistics. With the upcoming elections in most of the 13 congressional districts of the state, our agency has been hired to provide a detailed research on crime rates in the state and how best to provide an actionable set of policy recommendations -- so that the candidate could lay those out to the election going public and hopefully also sway indepenedents in their favor.

Research question¶

Our project aims to determine whether wage increases in one industry are able to reduce crime. It is commonly known that crime tends to correlate with factors such as higher population density and urban areas; however, there has been less research on the effect of wages on an area's crime rate.

Nonetheless, we accept that while government policies are able to affect other industries (e.g., through the minimum wage), if most of the employees in an industry already make more that the minimum wage, that effect is significantly dampened. However, government wages can be potentially affected by policy much more directly.

Thus given this potentially actionable policy recommendation that might be obtained from our research, we seek to determine whether wage increases in government jobs are able to reduce crime.

Based on the results of this analysis, we aim to recommend whether our political compaign should advocate for higher government wages as well as potentially continue research in wages within other industries. Note that whether or not economic prosperity has an effect on crime, it continues to be a worthy goal with many potential positive effects in other parts of our constituents lives; additional research will be required to determine the effects on other aspects of quality-of-life.

Methodology and EDA¶

We use data from C. Cornwell and W. Trumball (1994), “Estimating the Economic Model of Crime with Panel Data,” Review of Economics and Statistics 76, 360-366.

We start by reading in the data and checking then number of blank cells. We see that almost all of the columns have 6 nulls which are caused by reading in empty rows at the bottom of the dataframe. We remove these data points.

Taking a look at the summary of our data, we see that

  1. year is a constant and can be removed as the min, median, mean, max, etc. are all the same
  2. prbarr, probability of arrest, and prbconv, probability of conviction, have maximum values that are larger than 100%. Probabilities shouldn't have values over 100%. As we do not know if these data points were miss-entered and were supposed to be very low (e.g., 1.09 should have been 0.109) or were supposed to simply be at 100% (very high), it is safer for us just to remove these data points.
  3. wser, wages in the services industry, seems to have a maximum significantly larger than the median, mean and the quartiles, which seems to indicate that there is a significant outlier. If we decide to use this data point in our models, we'll have to take a closer look to determine whether this point should be retained or removed.

Because we're interested in the economic determinants of crime, we have decided to define the average number of crimes per person crmrte as our endogenous variable that we will regress.

Next, we look at the correlations between our variables (below) to look for potentially informative features as well as multi-collinearity. Even though there are a number of variables that are correlated with each other (e.g., all of the wage variables), we do not see any perfect multi-collinearity in the correlation matrix.

In [64]:
correlations <- cor(data)
corrplot(correlations, type="lower", method='circle', main="Correlation Plot")

We do see that the following variables are most correlated with crime rate:

  • wage related variables: wcon, wtuc, wtrd, wfir, wser, wmfg, wfed, wsta, wloc
  • population density variables
  • police presence and conviction variables

Our first model will only look at crime rate regressed on the wage in government jobs, wfed, wsta, wloc. However, as this does not take into account of important latent variables that also have a strong impact on crime (e.g., population density, police presence, tax rate), we build a second model with both the wage variable and key co-variates included. This way, we are able to isolate the effect of wages on crime without the interference of some of the key latent variables.

Lastly, we create a larger model with all of the main variables included to further isolate the effect of wages on crime. After each model, we will discuss the potential effects of omitted latent variables that we either have not yet included into the model or do not have data for.

Note that for our non-wage-related variables, we transform them (e.g., log, sqrt) as necessary to optimize the strength of their relationship with crime rate. Even though, it reduces the explainability of the non-wage-related variables, our key focus is on the effect of wages on crime anyway. By controlling as much as possible for the effect of other variables (by optimally transforming them to have a strong linear relationship with crime rate), we can focus more on the incremental impact of wages on crime. In other words, we are controlling for otherwise omitted latent relationships (e.g., non-linear) from other variables that may be affecting our wage variables.

We will need to take a closer look at our wage and crime rate variables in the section below before determining whether we want to transform them (e.g., potentially for a more robust model) or keep them untransformed (e.g., potentially for easier interpretability).

Note that we've chosen to exclude the following columns:

  • urban
  • county
  • mix

We exclude urban because it is defined as basically a calculated variable from density (based on the definition given in Cornwell & Trumball). We exclude county because it is an identifier column and not a characteristic. And lastly, we exclude mix because it is a descriptor of types of crime and thus not a possible causal variable of crime itself.

Model 1¶

We first take a look at the distribution of each of our variables. They all look roughly normal although there is some right skew in crmrte. wfed, wsta, and wloc are all roughly normally distributed.

Because we have a large sample, the right skew in crmrte should not be an issue due to the CLT. Nonetheless, we take a look at the log transformed version of crmrte and see that it is significantly more normal. Because we are able to keep our interpretability even with a log transform, we decide to do so.

We see that the log transformed wage variables have a similar distribution to what they had prior to the transformation. Because they do not seem to become more skewed and because a log-transform of wages helps for interpretability (e.g., \$300 increase may be small when you're earning \\$5000 but large when you're earning \$100), we decide to log-transform the three wage variables as well. When we log-transform, we're looking at the change in percentage rather than change in absolute number, which makes sense for wages (e.g., 10% increase in wages).

Our first model regresses crime rate on the average weekly wage of different government jobs. We see that these variables are able to explain about 27% of the variability in the crime rate (based on adjusted R2).

Analysis of CLM assumptions:¶

Following are the CLM assumptions:¶

  1. Linear population model
  2. Random Sampling
  3. No perfect multicollinearity
  4. Zero-conditional mean
  5. Homoskedasticity
  6. Normality of Errors

Following first two assumptions should hold for all subsequent linear models:¶

  1. Linear population model: we have created a linear population model using lm() and hence the condition of linearity of coefficients is satisfied

  2. Random Sampling: we are entirely certain whether or not this data is randomly sampled. Even though we have 90 out of 100 counties represented in our dataset, the summary statistics for each of the counties may or may not have been randomly sampled. For example, for wages, it is unclear whether the researchers had sampled wages from the richest areas in a county or whether wages was truly randomly sampled. Even though we cannot confirm that the data is i.i.d., for the remainder of the model, we will place our faith in Cornwell and Trumbull and assume that the data is randomly sampled.

  3. No perfect multicollinearity: we have created correlation tables below and do not find any values of 1 between different variables, hence the no perfect multicollinearity assumption holds too.

Following tests applied for zero-conditional mean and homoskedasticity error assumptions:¶

  1. Zero-conditional mean: In the Residuals vs Fitted plot, we see that the red smoothing line is almost flat, indicating that the conditional mean is roughly zero

  2. Homoskedasticity: In the Scale-Location plot we see that the smoothing line has a bit of a U-bend shape, which indicates that there may be a bit of heteroskedasticity. The Breusch-Pagan test indicates a p-value < 0.05, leading us to reject the null hypothesis of homoskedasticity. Thus, we will use the heteroskedastic robust errors.

  3. Normality of Errors: Our QQ plot shows evidence of some non-normality, but is overall relatively normal as most of the points show up on the diagonal line. The Shapiro-Wilk test shows a p-value > 0.05, meaning we cannot reject the null hypothesis that our errors are normal.

After accounting for heteroskedasticity using robust standard errors, we see that wfed is our significicant variable. In particular, it seems that every 1% increase in federal wages seems to correlate with a 1.4% increase in crime rate. The wsta and wloc features are not significant in this model. However, as we will discuss below, the counterintuitive result with higher wages correlating with higher crime is likely due to hidden variables that were not included in this model.

Some of the major omitted variables that we believe could have a significant impact on crime rates include the population density, the police presence within an area, and the tax per capita.

  • Density: As seen in the scatter plot below, population density is most likely positively correlated with both crime rate as well as wages (as wages tend to be higher in cities, which have higher population densities); we also see this in the calculated correlation. Because the omitted population density variable is positively correlated with both our endogenous and included exogenous variables, it is likely artificially increasing the modeled effect of the included exogenous variables. Said another way, because positive effect of population density on crime is not included, it is partially included in the wage variables, causing the coefficients/effect of the wage variables on crime to be more positive than they may be in reality.

  • Police Presence: Police presence tends to be higher in urban areas and areas with higher crime. Because these urban areas also tend to places with higher wages and costs of living, this omitted variable likely results in a negative bias once we control for density.

  • Taxpc: Finally, tax per capita will be higher in areas with higher wages (the rich pay more in absolute taxes). Nevertheless, because nicer, richer areas (once you control for dense urban regions) will tend to have lower crime, this omitted variable may cause a slight negative bias once we control for density.

In order to control for some of the effects of the omitted variables, we next create a second model with our model-1 coefficients in addition to:

  • taxpc
  • polpc
  • density

Therefore: Model 2 = Model 1 + taxpc, density, polpc

Model 2¶

In our second model, we want to control for the effect of the hidden variables that may be artificially increasing the modeled effect of our government wage variables in model one. Therefore, we add in taxpc, density, and polpc to control for these effects.

Above, we had discussed the potential effect of each additional variable on crime rate. In our modeling below, we'll be assessing each of the model coefficients for taxpc, density, and polpc to determine the actual effect of each feature on crime (positive or negative) as well as the strength of the effect.

Once again, we take a look at a histogram of our new variables. While tax per capita, density, police per capita are all right skewed. We can see that the log transforms of the tax per capita and police per capita are slightly more normally distributed, so we take the log of those features. We leave density untransformed.

Running a new model with the our new variables shows that these features together are able to explain about 50% of the variation in the crime rate (based on the adjusted R-squared). In particular, now that we have controlled for the effect of taxpc, density, and polpc, we see that federal wages and local wages seem to have a slight positive effect on crime rate, while state wages has a slight negative effect on crime rate. Taxpc, desnity, and polpc all appear to have a positive effect on crime rate.

Prior to looking at significance of the features, we first re-evaluate our CLM assumptions.

  1. Zero-conditional mean: In the Residuals vs Fitted plot, we see that the red smoothing line is almost flat, indicating that the conditional mean is roughly zero. Though there is some deviation, it is not huge.

  2. Homoskedasticity: In the Scale-Location plot we see that the smoothing line has a definite slant, indicating that the variance of the errors decreases as the predicted values go up.. The Breusch-Pagan test indicates a p-value < 0.05, leading us to reject the null hypothesis of homoskedasticity. Thus, we will use the heteroskedastic robust errors.

  3. Normality of Errors: Our QQ plot shows evidence of some non-normality, but is overall relatively normal as most of the points show up on the diagonal line. The Shapiro-Wilk test shows a p-value > 0.05, meaning we cannot reject the null hypothesis that our errors are normal.

After accounting for heteroskedasticity using robust standard errors, we see that density is our one significicant variable. It seems that for every increase in density of one person per square mile, the crime rate increases by 0.12%. 1% increase in federal wages seems to correlate with a 1.4% increase in crime rate.

In particular, we note that once we control for density, polpc, and taxpc, it seems that the government wages do not have a significant effect on the crime rate within a county, which, for our policy decisions, seems to indicate that raising government wages will not have an effect on crime rates. Instead, it seems that policies geared toward enticing people toward suburbs to decrease the population in the highest crime rate, urban populations may help reduce the crime rate a decent amount. Before we come to any firm conclusions though, we need to consider additional hidden variables.

In particular, we look at:

  • pctymle: because young males tend to be more pre-disposed to criminal activity, they will tend to have a positive effect on crime rate. At the same time, they tend to be earlier in their careers and will have lower wages.
  • prbconv and prbarr: because a higher arrest rate and higher conviction rate make the potential cost of committing a crime significantly higher, we believe that this is likely negatively correlated with crime. In adddition, higher government wages may indicate a more stringent government, potentially correlated with a higher conviction and arrest rate.

Model 3¶

Lastly, we will turn to the following remaining variables to create a final model with additional features that we believe might affect crime rate, even if we believe the effect may be minimal:

  • pctymle
  • prbconv
  • prbarr

Our final model is: Model 3 = Model 2 + pctymle, prbconv, prbarr

We wanted to include these variables that we believe potentially have a strong effect on crime rates in order to decrease the effects of omitted variable bias.

Once again, we take a look at a histogram of our new variables. We can see that the probability of conviction and arrest are pretty normally distributed. While percent young male is right skewed, we decide not to transform this variable as log, sqrt, etc. transforms of this percentage variable decrease explainability drastically.

Running a new model with the our new variables shows that these features together are able to explain about 62% of the variation in the crime rate (based on the adjusted R-squared). In particular, now that we have controlled for the effect of taxpc, density, polpc, pctymle, prbarr, and prbconv, we see that federal wages and local wages continue to have a slight positive effect on crime rate, while state wages has a slight negative effect on crime rate. While prbarr and prbconv have negative effects on crime rate, as we had expected, polpc and taxpc seem to have positive effects on crime rate, contrary to our initial thoughts.

Prior to looking at significance of the features, we first re-evaluate our CLM assumptions.

Analysis of CLM assumptions:¶

Following are the CLM assumptions:¶

  1. Linear population model
  2. Random Sampling
  3. No perfect multicollinearity
  4. Zero-conditional mean
  5. Homoskedasticity
  6. Normality of Errors

Analysis:¶

  1. Linear population model: we have created a linear population model using lm() and hence the condition of linearity of coefficients is satisfied

  2. Random Sampling: we are entirely certain whether or not this data is randomly sampled. Even though we have 90 out of 100 counties represented in our dataset, the summary statistics for each of the counties may or may not have been randomly sampled. Please refer to model 1 for a more in depth explanation.

  3. No perfect multicollinearity: we have created correlation tables below and do not find any values of 1 between different variables, hence the no perfect multicollinearity assumption holds too.

Conclusion and recommendations¶

Overall, despite having included iteratively more variables into our model, there are still a significant number of omitted variables that may be confounding our research.

The following sources of omitted variable bias will tend to have positive correlation with crime rate:

  • Gang activity: gangs tend to be direct causes of crime in regions where they are based, regardless of the economic prosperity, density, or arrest rates in that region. Even though some of these factors may push the level of gang activity up or down, it makes sense that gang activity will always have a positive effect on crime.
  • Unemployment rate: if you are unemployed you tend to have less money, and having less money will increase the chance that one might commit a crime. Poorer areas tend to have more crime.
  • Single parenthood: less oversight of young males may lead these individuals to become more reckless and potentially show less regard for others as well as property, leading to higher crime rates
  • Guns per capita: easier access to weapons may lead to a higher propensity to commit crimes

The following sources of omitted variable bias may have negative correlation with crime rate:

  • Education rate: higher high school graduation rate usually means that most students learn to stay out of trouble during their formative years and onward, leading to lower crime
  • Health care: easier access to healthcare may lead to 1) better mental health among citizens 2) fewer issues with drug addiction both potentially leading to lower crime rates
  • Weather: because there are more opportunities to be outside in good climates, where groups of strangers may congregate, there will be potentially higher crime rates in warmer climates. On the flip side, in colder climates, people tend to stay in-doors, decreasing the chance that they will commit a crime

In our initial basic model, wfed, the federal wages seems to have a significant positive effect on crime rate. However, it becomes evident that part of that significance is due to omitted variables as in the second model, density and police presence seem to have significant effects instead.

Ultimately, in our third model, we see that the probability of arrest and percentage of young males have the highest statistical significance followed by density and wfed.

In particular, we see that for every 10 percentage point increase in the probability of arrest, crime goes down by 0.15%. For percent young male, every 10 percentage point increase in the percentage of young males tends to increase crime rate by 0.4%. For density, every one person increase per square mile leads to a 0.065% increase in crime. Lastly, each 10% increase in federal wages, tends to lead to 9.39% increase in crime.

Ultimately, even though the probability of arrest is highly stastically significant, it does not appear to have a large practical significance due to it's small coefficient. In addition, the max value is capped at 1. Though percent young male, has a larger practical effect, it is important to note that percentage young male is also capped physically at 1 and 0. Density and federal wages appear to have a much larger practical effect on crime. Nevertheless, we believe that the effect of wfed may be more associative than causal as crmrte may be explained by several omitted variables outline above in our text.

Policy recommendations¶

Originally we were exploring the idea that whether government wages in the North Carolina congressional districts were related to crime statistics in the state. We were hoping to find a possible statistical significance of wages on crime rates, through which we could implement some economic or social sector programs related to jobs and labor growth.

However, we were not able to find a strong statistical or practical effect of state or local wages on crime. While federal wages did seem to have a strong positive effect on crime, we believe that that is likely due to omitted variable bias as it is not immediately clear why federal wages would lead to higher crime.

Instead, we found that population density has a relatively strong effect on crime rates. Thus, we recommend encourage a rejuvenation of suburban and exurban areas around bigger cities to promote the decrease urban congestion and thereby reduce population density of the area:

  • Housing subsidies for individuals moving into suburbs from urban areas
  • Investing in community centers / restaurants / malls in suburbs to entice citizens to move
  • Increasing public transit to make the commute in and out of the suburbs more convenient
